title: For Sale:  Stock Refinishing Service
postcontent:
Have an old stock that has seen better days? or maybe you are disappointed with your brand new rifle, most new stocks come with a cheap finish from the factory, this finish consists of a stain mixed with a sealer which hides the beautiful grain underneath, they are also weak and prone to chipping and scratches.

    I can refinish those stocks and make them look better than they did new, I can use a polyurethane finish in a High gloss, Medium gloss, or Satin, this finish will be beautiful and will stand up to anything you will reasonably put it through. I do not add stain unless the customer asks for it, I don't recommend stain because it can make the grain cloudy.

     I can also do a Hand-Rubbed, Boiled Linseed Oil finish, while not as durable as a Polyurethane finish, it is very good looking and will make the natural grain stand out. this finish is not recommended for hunting guns or any guns that will be exposed to excessive moisture.

     Pricing starts at $100 for a base polyurethane finish for an uncheckered stock, this means I will chemically strip the existing finish and apply a poly of your choice, the grain will be unfilled, but still visually appealing and durable. additional add-ons are as follows:
for stocks with checkering, add $20, for a total of $120.
for stain, any color of your choosing, add $5.
for filled grain (this makes the surface as smooth as glass), add $20.
or if you don't want a polyurethane finish, a hand rubbed BLO finish is $100. 

     If you send me pictures we can discuss pricing if there is heavy wear on the stock and it needs repairs.

     Email or call 1-580-three seven zero-9468 for any questions.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Extremely rare WW2 German Battlefield photo album Alligtator skinned leather
postcontent:
Very rare one of a kind piece of ww2 history
Original photographs from ww2
 You simply can not go somewhere and buy one of these like a lot of military collectibles
 I am relinquishing parts of my ww2 collection so that others may enjoy them.
 This is an alligator skinned leather photo album from the tours of the very first anti aircraft/anti tank unit that Germany created for world war two
 I Flak/Regt 5 
 Alligator skin/leather is in really good shape for it's age and you have to see it to appreciate it.It has a leather strip tied that is binding the pages to the album.Pages are in great shape and still have the onion paper dividers so the pictures don't stick together.
 I have all of the photos removed so they can be viewed without man handling the album it self.(almost 100 pictures)
 There were only six of these units created and they never existed before ww2.This was the very first unit created and remained in service the longest (unit created 10 January,1935 and remained in service until the end of the war in 1945)
 http://www.ww2.dk/ground/flak/flargt5.html
 http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flak_corps 
 This album chronicles the units tours through the war.

 Some of the pictures are nicely captioned and dated and include pictures of bombed and burnt out vehicles,artillery,soldiers digging graves and trenches,the huge range finders they used and also a lot of candid shots of the soldiers smiling and having fun playing soccer in the dirt,stacks of wine bottles,playing music ,hanging out in their field tents,etc

 Anyway,i have decided to let this piece go.This is a must have for anybody who is a ww2 buff.Like I said before,this is simply not something you can go out and buy and there will NEVER be another one

 I have added a few pictures here but can take and email more although it would be best to meet and let you see it in person. 
Will trade for:
Firearms,modern firearms,c&r,hunting rifles,pistols.......will entertain all other trades

title: For Sale:  Custom Stock Refinishing
postcontent:
Have an old stock that has seen better days? or maybe you are disappointed with your brand new rifle, most new stocks come with a cheap finish from the factory, this finish consists of a stain mixed with a sealer which hides the beautiful grain underneath, they are also weak and prone to chipping and scratches.

I can refinish those stocks and make them look better than they did new, I can use a polyurethane finish in a High gloss, Medium gloss, or Satin, this finish will be beautiful and will stand up to anything you will reasonably put it through. I do not add stain unless the customer asks for it, I don't recommend stain because it can make the grain cloudy.

I can also do a Hand-Rubbed, Boiled Linseed Oil finish, while not as durable as a Polyurethane finish, it is very good looking and will make the natural grain stand out. this finish is not recommended for hunting guns or any guns that will be exposed to excessive moisture.

Pricing starts at $100 for a base polyurethane finish for an uncheckered stock, this means I will chemically strip the existing finish and apply a poly of your choice, the grain will be unfilled, but still visually appealing and durable. additional add-ons are as follows:
for stocks with checkering, add $20, for a total of $120.
for stain, any color of your choosing, add $5.
for filled grain (this makes the surface as smooth as glass), add $20.
or if you don't want a polyurethane finish, a hand rubbed BLO finish is $100. 

If you send me pictures we can discuss pricing if there is heavy wear on the stock and it needs repairs.

Email or call 1-580-three seven zero-9468 for any questions.

title: For Sale:  Custom stock finishes
postcontent:
Have an old stock that has seen better days? or maybe you are disappointed with your brand new rifle, most new stocks come with a cheap finish from the factory, this finish consists of a stain mixed with a sealer which hides the beautiful grain underneath, they are also weak and prone to chipping and scratches.

I can refinish those stocks and make them look better than they did new, I can use a polyurethane finish in a High gloss, Medium gloss, or Satin, this finish will be beautiful and will stand up to anything you will reasonably put it through. I do not add stain unless the customer asks for it, I don't recommend stain because it can make the grain cloudy.

I can also do a Hand-Rubbed, Boiled Linseed Oil finish, while not as durable as a Polyurethane finish, it is very good looking and will make the natural grain stand out. this finish is not recommended for hunting guns or any guns that will be exposed to excessive moisture.

Pricing starts at $100 for a base polyurethane finish for an uncheckered stock, this means I will chemically strip the existing finish and apply a poly of your choice, the grain will be unfilled, but still visually appealing and durable. additional add-ons are as follows:
for stocks with checkering, add $20, for a total of $120.
for stain, any color of your choosing, add $5.
for filled grain (this makes the surface as smooth as glass), add $20.
or if you don't want a polyurethane finish, a hand rubbed BLO finish is $100. 

If you send me pictures we can discuss pricing if there is heavy wear on the stock and it needs repairs.

Email or call 1-580-three seven zero-9468 for any questions.

title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1903 "Hammerless" Pocket .32--Type 1--manf. 1906
postcontent:
This is a Colt Model 1903 "Hammerless" Pocket .32. The serial number is 48204, which puts its manufacture in 1906. All serial numbers are matching. 

This is the Type 1 variation. It has the early Type 1 style lettering, 4" barrel, and the fired-blue barrel takedown bushing. Grips are correct and in perfect shape.

The finish is probably 70% overall. The derioration of the bluing is most obvious on the left side of the slide, as shown in the pictures, and looks like holster wear.The right side retains around 90-95% of the original blue. All of the finish that is intact on the gun still has the same high luster that it had when it left the factory 107 years ago. I havent polished this gun at all (to keep patina), and you can still see my reflection in the finish on a cpl of the pics. A very small amount of slight pitting.

The gun is in pefect mechanical shape, and is still very tight. Action is still very smooth, and no rust inside or out.

Includes original magazine.

The bad--some minor scratching, and damage to the slidelock area. Both of these are to be expected from a 107 year old pistol though. The screw opposite the slidelock is damaged.

Overall this gun is easily a 7-7.5 out of 10. It is the lowest serial number Type 1 in this kind of shape that I have seen for sale under $1k.

Please contact me if you would like to see any other pictures.
